description:
secretx-keyring/src/lib.rs has the closure pattern `|e| SecretError::Backend { backend: "keyring", source: e.into() }` repeated 4 times: lines 118-121, 129-132, 136-139, 160-163, 169-172, 176-179. Each invocation differs only in the source binding name and the immediately surrounding context.

The sibling crate secretx-wolfhsm extracts this to a helper:
```rust
fn join_err(e: tokio::task::JoinError) -> SecretError {
    SecretError::Backend { backend: BACKEND, source: e.into() }
}
```
…called as `.map_err(join_err)?`.

For keyring, two helpers (or one generic) would cover the cases:
```rust
fn backend_err<E: std::error::Error + Send + Sync + 'static>(e: E) -> SecretError {
    SecretError::Backend { backend: BACKEND, source: Box::new(e) }
}
```

Net change: eliminates ~12 lines of duplication, makes the get/put method bodies show only their domain logic. Reads as net-positive after the change.

This is taste-adjacent but the duplication count justifies the abstraction — net negative abstraction concern (Section 3 of /review-myoss) does not apply because the helper saves more lines than it adds.
